ngs Falling]]''<br />(translated by [[Anne McLean]])\n|\n*[[Gerbrand Bakker (novelist)|Gerbrand Bakker]] \u2013 ''[[The Detour (novel)|The Detour]]'' (translated from Dutch by [[David Colmer]])\n*[[Michelle de Kretser]] \u2013 ''[[Questions of Travel]]''\n*[[Patrick Flanery]] \u2013 ''Absolution''\n*[[Karl Ove Knausg\u00e5rd]] \u2013 ''A Death In The Family'' (translated from Norwegian by Don Bartlett) (''My Struggle \u2013 First Book'')\n*[[Marie NDiaye]] \u2013 ''[[Three Strong Women]]'' (translated from French by John Fletcher)\n*[[Andr\u00e9s Neuman]] \u2013 ''Traveller of the Century'' (translated from Spanish by [[Nick Caistor]] and Lorenza Garcia)\n*[[Tan Twan Eng]] \u2013 ''[[The Garden of Evening Mists]]''\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| 2015\n| [[File:Jim crace 2009.jpg|100px]]\n| {{sortname|Jim|Crace}}<ref name=guardian2015>{{cite news|first=Alison|last=Flood|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/jun/17/impac-prize-goes-to-consummate-wordsmith-jim-crace-for-harvest|title=Impac prize goes to 'consummate wordsmith' Jim Crace for Harvest|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=17 June 2015|accessdate=18 June 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150618074032/http://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/jun/17/impac-prize-goes-to-consummate-wordsmith-jim-crace-for-harvest|archivedate=18 June 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| English\n| ''[[Harvest (Crace novel)|Harvest]]''\n|\n*[[Richard Flanagan]] \u2013 ''[[The Narrow Road to the Deep North (novel) |The Narrow Road to the Deep North]]''\n*[[Hannah Kent]] \u2013 ''[[Burial Rites]]''\n*[[Bernardo Kucinski]] \u2013 ''K'' (translated from Portuguese by Sue Branford)\n*[[Andre\u00ef Makine]] \u2013 ''Brief Loves That Live Forever'' (translated from French by [[Geoffrey Strachan]])\n*[[Colum McCann]] \u2013 ''[[TransAtlantic (novel)|TransAtlantic]]''\n*[[Mahi Binebine]] \u2013 ''Horses of God'' (translated from French by Lulu Norman)\n*[[Chimamanda Ngozi Adichie]] \u2013 ''[[Americanah]]''\n*[[Alice McDermott]] \u2013 ''Someone''\n*[[Roxana Barry Robinson|Roxana Robinson]] \u2013 ''Sparta''\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| 2016\n| align=center| &ndash;\n| {{sortname|Akhil|Sharma}}<ref name=w2016/><ref name=guardian2016>{{cite news|first=Alsion|last=Flood|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/jun/09/akhil-sharma-wins-100000-dublin-international-literary-award|title=Akhil Sharma wins \u20ac100,000 Dublin International literary award|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=9 June 2016|accessdate=9 June 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160609132846/https://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/jun/09/akhil-sharma-wins-100000-dublin-international-literary-award|archivedate=9 June 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| English\n| ''[[Family Life (novel)|Family Life]]''\n|\n*[[Javier Cercas]] \u2013 ''Outlaws'' (Translated from Spanish by [[Anne McLean]])\n*[[Mary Costello]] \u2013 ''Academy Street''\n*[[Dave Eggers]] \u2013 ''[[Your Fathers, Where Are They? And the Prophets, Do They Live Forever?]]''\n*[[Jenny Erpenbeck]] \u2013 ''The End of Days'' (Translated from German by Susan Bernofsky)\n*[[Marlon James (novelist)|Marlon James]] \u2013 ''[[A Brief History of Seven Killings]]''\n*[[Michel Laub]] \u2013 ''Diary of the Fall'' (Translated from Portuguese by Margaret Jull Costa)\n*[[Scholastique Mukasonga]] \u2013 ''[[Our Lady of the Nile]]'' (Translated from French by Melanie Mauthner)\n*[[Jenny Offill]] \u2013 ''Dept. of Speculation''\n*[[Marilynne Robinson]] \u2013 ''[[Lila (Robinson novel)|Lila]]''\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| 2017\n| [[File:JE Agualusa.jpg|100px]]\n|  {{sortname|Jos\u00e9 Eduardo|Agualusa}}<ref name=dublinlitwinner2017>{{cite news|url=http://www.dublinliteraryaward.ie/news/the-2017-winner-is-announced/|title=The 2017 winner is announced!|date=21 June 2017|accessdate=21 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170621180526/http://www.dublinliteraryaward.ie/news/the-2017-winner-is-announced/|archivedate=21 June 2017|df=dmy-all| publisher=International DUBLIN Library Award Office}}</ref>\n| Portuguese\n| ''[[A General Theory of Oblivion]]''<br>(translated by [[Daniel Hahn]])\n| \n*[[Mia Couto]] \u2013 ''Confession of the Lioness'' (Translated from Portuguese by David Brookshaw)\n*[[Anne Enright]] \u2013 ''[[The Green Road (Enright novel)|The Green Road]]''\n*[[Kim Leine]] \u2013 ''[[The Prophets of Eternal Fjord]]'' (Translated from Danish by Martin Aitken)\n*[[Valeria Luiselli]] \u2013 ''The Story of My Teeth'' (Translated from Spanish by Christina MacSweeney)\n*[[Viet Thanh Nguyen]] - ''[[The Sympathizer]]''\n*[[Chinelo Okparanta]] \u2013 ''[[Under the Udala Trees]]''\n*[[Orhan Pamuk]] \u2013 ''[[A Strangeness in My Mind]]'' (Translated from Turkish by Ekin Oklap)\n*[[Robert Seethaler]] \u2013 ''A Whole Life'' (Translated from German by Charlotte Collins)\n*[[Hanya Yanagihara]] \u2013 ''[[A Little Life]]''\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| 2018\n|[[File:Mike McCormack Bokm\u00e4ssan 2017.jpg|frameless]]\n|[[Mike McCormack (writer)|Mike McCormack]]<ref name=\":0\" />\n|English\n|''[[Solar Bones]]''\n|\n* [[Alina Bronsky]] \u2013 ''Baba Dunja's Last Love'' (Translated from German by Tim Mahr)\n* [[Yuri Herrera]] \u2013''The Transmigration of Bodies'' (Translated from Spanish by Lisa Dillman)\n* [[Roy Jacobsen]] \u2013 ''The Unseen'' (Translated from Norwegian by Don Bartlett and Don Shaw)\n* [[Han Kang]] \u2013 ''Human Acts'' (Translated from Korean by [[Deborah Smith (translator)|Deborah Smith]])\n* [[Eimear McBride]] \u2013 ''[[The Lesser Bohemians]]''\n* [[Antonio Moresco]] \u2013 ''Distant Light'' (Translated from Italian by [[Richard Dixon (translator)|Richard Dixon]])\n* [[Marie NDiaye]] \u2013 ''Ladivine'' (Translated from French by Jordan Stump)\n* [[Yewande Omotoso]] \u2013 ''The Woman Next Door''\n* [[Elizabeth Strout]] \u2013 ''[[My Name Is Lucy Barton]]''\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| 2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dublinliteraryaward.ie/2019-shortlist/|title=The 2019 Shortlist|access-date=5 April 2019|website=International Dublin Literary Award}}</ref>\n|\n|[[Emily Ruskovich]]\n|[[English language|English]]\n|''[[Idaho (novel)|Idaho]]'' {{double dagger}}\n|\n* [[Mathias \u00c9nard]] \u2013 ''Compass'' (Translated from French by Charlotte Mandell)\n* [[Emily Fridlund]] \u2013''[[History of Wolves]]''\n* [[Mohsin Hamid]] \u2013 ''Exit West''\n* [[Bernard MacLaverty]] \u2013 ''Midwinter Break''\n* [[Jon McGregor]] \u2013 ''Reservoir 13''\n* [[Sally Rooney]] \u2013 ''[[Conversations with Friends]]''\n* [[George Saunders]] \u2013 ''Lincoln in the Bardo''\n* [[Rachel Seiffert]] \u2013 ''A Boy in Winter''\n* [[Kamila Shamsie]] \u2013 ''[[Home Fire (novel)|Home Fire]]''\n|}\n*{{double dagger}} &ndash; debut novel\n\n===Wins by language===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Total\n! scope=\"col\"| Language\n! scope=\"col\"| Years\n|-\n|'''14'''\n!scope=\"row\"| English\n|1996, 1999, 2000, 2001, 2005, 2006, 2008, 2009, 2011, 2012, 2013, 2015, 2016, 2018, 2019\n|-\n|'''2'''\n!scope=\"row\"| French\n|2002, 2004\n|-\n|'''2'''\n!scope=\"row\"| Spanish\n|1997, 2014\n|-\n|'''1'''\n!scope=\"row\"| German\n|1998\n|-\n|'''1'''\n!scope=\"row\"| Turkish\n|2003\n|-\n|'''1'''\n!scope=\"row\"| Norwegian\n|2007\n|-\n|'''1'''\n!scope=\"row\"| Dutch\n|2010\n|-\n|'''1'''\n!scope=\"row\"| Portuguese\n|2017\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.dublinliteraryaward.ie/}}\n\n{{International Dublin Literary Award}}\n\n{{featured list}}\n[[Category:Awards by the municipality of Dublin (city)]]\n[[Category:Awards established in 1996]]\n[[Category:English-language literary awards]]\n[[Category:Fiction awards]]\n[[Category:International literary awards]]\n[[Category:Irish literary awards]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|International literary award, administered by Dublin City Libraries}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=April 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2011}}\n{{Infobox award\n| name           = International Dublin Literary Award\n| image          = \n| image_size     = \n| reward         = [[Euro|\u20ac]]100,000\n| description    = ''a novel written in or translated into English''\n| presenter      = [[Dublin City Public Libraries and Archive]]\n| location       = [[Dublin]], Ireland\n| year           = 1996\n| holder      = [[Emily Ruskovich]] for ''[[Idaho (novel)|Idaho]]'' (2019)\n| former name    = International IMPAC Dublin Literary Award\n| most_awards    = 1 (all)\n| most_nominations = 3 \u2013 [[Colm T\u00f3ib\u00edn]], [[Colum McCann]] (author)<br>3 \u2013 [[Anne McLean]] (translator)\n| website        = {{url|www.dublinliteraryaward.ie}} \n}}\nThe '''International Dublin Literary Award''' ({{lang-ga|Duais Liteartha Idirn\u00e1isi\u00fanta Bhaile \u00c1tha Chliath}}) is presented each year for a novel written or translated into English. It promotes excellence in world literature and is solely sponsored by Dublin City Council, Ireland.  At [[Euro|\u20ac]]100,000, the award is one of the [[List of richest literary prizes|richest literary prizes in the world]]. If the winning book is a translation (as it has been nine times), the prize is divided between the writer and the translator, with the writer receiving \u20ac75,000 and the translator \u20ac25,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dutchnews.nl/news/archives/2010/06/dutch_writer_wins_worlds_bigge.php|title=Dutch writer wins world's biggest literature prize|date=18 June 2010|work=DutchNews.nl|accessdate=18 June 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100619150849/http://www.dutchnews.nl/news/archives/2010/06/dutch_writer_wins_worlds_bigge.php|archivedate=19 June 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  The first award was made in 1996 to [[David Malouf]] for his English language novel ''[[Remembering Babylon]]''.<ref name=firstwin/>\n\nNominations are submitted by [[public library|public libraries]] worldwide \u2013 over 400 library systems in 177 countries worldwide are invited to nominate books each year \u2013 from which the shortlist and the eventual winner are selected by an international panel of judges (which changes each year). The most recent winner is [[Emily Ruskovich]] who won for her novel ''[[Idaho (novel)|Idaho]]''.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.dublinliteraryaward.ie/news/mike-mc-cormacks-solar-bones-is-the-winner-of-the-2018-award/|title=Mike Mc Cormack\u2019s Solar Bones is the winner of the 2018 award! {{!}} International DUBLIN Literary Award|website=www.dublinliteraryaward.ie|language=en-US|access-date=2018-06-16}}</ref>\n\n==Eligibility and procedure==\nThe prize is open to novels written in any language and by authors of any nationality, provided the work has been published in English or English translation.  The presentation of the award is post-dated by two years from the date of publication. Thus, to win an award in 2017, the work must have been published in 2015. If it is an English translation, the work must have been published in its original language between two and six years before its translation.<ref name=impac-faq>{{Cite web | url = http://www.dublinliteraryaward.ie/faqs/ | publisher= Dublin City Public Libraries| accessdate= 25 July 2017|title = FAQs}}</ref>  The scope for inclusion has been subject to criticism;  according to ''[[The Irish Times]]'' journalist [[Eileen Battersby]], \"many of the titles are already well known even at the time of the publication of the long list.\"<ref name=\"dublinlitwinner2017a\">{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/books/jos%C3%A9-eduardo-agualusa-wins-100-000-international-dublin-literary-award-1.3127773|title=Jos\u00e9 Eduardo Agualusa wins \u20ac100,000 International Dublin Literary Award|last1=Battersby|first1=Eileen|date=21 June 2017|work=The Irish Times|accessdate=21 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Dublin City Public Libraries and Archive|Dublin City Public Libraries]] seek nominations from 400 [[Public library|public libraries]] from major cities across the world.  Libraries can apply to be considered for inclusion in the nomination process.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.dublinliteraryaward.ie/libraries-2017/ | title = Libraries 2017| publisher = Dublin City Public Libraries | accessdate = 25 July 2017}}</ref> The longlist is announced in October or November of each year, and the shortlist (up to 10 titles) is announced in March or April of the following year.  The longlist and shortlist are chosen by an international panel of judges which rotates each year. [[Allen Weinstein]] was the non-voting chair of the panel from 1996 to 2003. As of 2017, the former Chief Judge of a US Court of Appeals, [[Eugene R. Sullivan]], is the non-voting chair.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.dublinliteraryaward.ie/2017-judging-panel/ | title = 2017 Judging Panel| publisher = Dublin City Public Libraries | accessdate = 26 July 2017}}</ref>  The winner of the award is announced each June.<ref name=impac-faq />\n\n==History==\nThe award was established in 1994 as the '''International IMPAC Dublin Literary Award''', a joint initiative of [[Dublin City Council]] and the American productivity company IMPAC, which had its European headquarters in Dublin.<ref name=hilliard/>  James Irwin, president of IMPAC, established the prize money at \u20ac100,000. A trust fund was established to pay for the award and its maintenance. The award has been administered by Dublin City Public Libraries since its inception. IMPAC went defunct in the late-2000s when its founder and president James Irwin died in 2009.<ref name=hilliard/> In late 2013, the trust fund became exhausted and there was no money left to run the award.<ref name=hilliard/> The council agreed to step in and continue funding the award under the same brand name of the now-defunct company while seeking a new sponsor.<ref name=hilliard>{{cite web|work=The Irish Times|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/new-sponsor-sought-for-100-000-impac-literary-award-1.2232674|title=New sponsor sought for \u20ac100,000 Impac literary Award|last=Hilliard|first=Mark|date=May 31, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150718232658/http://www.irishtimes.com/culture/new-sponsor-sought-for-100-000-impac-literary-award-1.2232674|archivedate=18 July 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It was reported that the council paid \u20ac100,000 for the prize plus \u20ac80,250 in administration costs in 2015.<ref name=hilliard/> The award was subsequently renamed the International DUBLIN Literary Award in November 2015.\n\nDescribing the award as \"the most eclectic and unpredictable of the literary world's annual gongs\", the journalist Michelle Pauli posed the question in relation to the longlist for the 2004 edition, \"Where would you find [[Michael Dobbs]] and [[Tony Parsons (British journalist)|Tony Parsons]] up against [[Umberto Eco]] and [[Milan Kundera]] for a \u20ac100,000 prize?\"<ref>{{cite news|first=Michelle|last=Pauli|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2003/nov/18/news.impacprize?INTCMP=ILCNETTXT3487|title=Bestsellers make impact on eclectic longlist|work=The Guardian|date=18 November 2003|accessdate=18 November 2003|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715090333/http://www.theguardian.com/books/2003/nov/18/news.impacprize?INTCMP=ILCNETTXT3487|archivedate=15 July 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n\n===Winners and shortlists===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!scope=\"col\" | Year\n!scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| Image\n!scope=\"col\" | Winner\n!scope=\"col\" | Language\n!scope=\"col\" | Novel\n!scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"|Shortlisted<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.dublinliteraryaward.ie/?s=shortlist |publisher = International DUBLIN Literary Award Office|  title= Search Results for: shortlist| accessdate = 22 June 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| 1996\n| [[File:David Malouf.JPG|100px]]\n| {{sortname|David|Malouf}}<ref name=firstwin>{{Cite web | url = https://www.irishtimes.com/news/malouf-wins-first-impac-literary-award-1.59034| work=The Irish Times 